SALES FORECASTING FOR SMALL BASKET¶

Business case¶

Small basket is a huge online/mobile based grocery retailer in India, founded in 2011. Small basket is trying to manage its supply chain and delivery partners and would like to accurately forecast the sales. Sales forecasting aides in the following:

  • Allows to plan ahead and develop an effective sales plan. Prevent possible problems from occurring.

  • Allocate budget. Knowing whether to spend or conserve with confidence in order to support dealerships. A sales forecast can help a company make sensible investments and avoid purchasing too much or too little stock.

  • Assess sales performance provides an idea of how your sales teams are performing both individually and as a whole.
  • Set goals - With a firm indication of your expected sales, you can set your team goals that you are confident are achievable because they are based on statistical data. More attainable goals will create fair competition.

Problem Statement¶

Small Basket is trying to manage its supply chain and delivery partners and would like to accurately forecast the sales for the period starting from 1st January 2019 to 15th January 2019 across several locations and product categories.

The data provided contains item details, daily item unit sales, location details and daily transactions made by each location. Using historical data, we can use these details to train a model that can predict the unit sales for each item for each location. This will help the business to plan ahead on future stock and dealerships.

The Machine Learning Pipeline¶

  • Problem Statement: Sales Forecasting for SmallBasket.
  • Domain Understanding, deciding the performance metric: MAPE
  • Data Extraction: Train data
  • Data Understanding: Summary Statistics,aggregation, Missing values etc
  • Data Preprocessing: Data type conversion, train validation split.
  • Feature Engineering: Created features like day_of_week, isWeekend, month, year.
  • Visualization: Top 10 items sold, distribution of locations in different cities, states, types and clusters. Total unit sales of different location etc.
  • Model Building: using Random Forest, Decision Tree, XG Boost, Light Gradient Boosting Model and Neural Networks
  • Performance tuning of the model and performance on unseen data: Used Cross validation and gridsearch for performance tuning.
  • Summary,conclusion and recommendations to the business.

def read_pkl_file(year):
  if(type(year)==int):
    infile=open('data_'+str(year),'rb')
  else:
    infile=open('data_'+year,'rb')
  loaded_pkl=pkl.load(infile)
  infile.close()
  return loaded_pkl

import numpy as np

def get_mape(y_true, y_pred): 
    y_true, y_pred = np.array(y_true), np.array(y_pred)
    return np.mean(np.abs((y_true - y_pred) / y_true)) * 100

def prep_data(dat):
  dat['year'] = dat['year'].astype('int32')
  dat['month'] = dat['month'].astype('int8')
  x_train = dat[dat['year']==2017]
  x_train = dat[(dat['month']>8)|(dat['month']==1)]
  y_train = (x_train['unit_sales'])
  #y_train['unit_sales']=y_train.astype('int32')
  x_train.drop(['year','date','unit_sales'],axis = 1,inplace=True)
  print(x_train.shape)
  print(y_train.shape)
  x_valid = dat[dat['year']==2018]
  x_valid = dat[dat['month']==1]
  y_valid = (x_valid['unit_sales'])
  #y_valid['unit_sales']=y_valid.astype('int32')
  x_valid.drop(['year','date','unit_sales'],axis =1,inplace=True)
  print(x_valid.shape)
  print(y_valid.shape)

  return x_train,y_train,x_valid,y_valid

def make_submision(test_preds,pred_file):
  test_data['unit_sales'] = test_preds

  pred_file = pd.merge(predictions,submit,on='id')
  pred_file.drop('unit_sales_x',axis = 1,inplace = True)
  pred_file.rename(columns = {"unit_sales_y":"unit_sales"},inplace=True)
  pred_file.to_csv('predictsDT.csv',index = False)

Random Forests¶

Gridsearch method is used for parameter tuning for different models.GridSearchCV lets you combine an estimator with a grid search preamble to tune hyper-parameters. The method picks the optimal parameter from the grid search and uses it with the estimator selected by the user.

Parameters tuned:n_estimators=defines the number of base estimators.;max_depth:maximum depth of the individual estimator.For good performance;max_features:The number of features to consider while searching for the best split.min_sample_leaf = minimum samples required in a terminal or leaf node.

XGBoost¶

XGBoost (extreme Gradient Boosting) is an advanced implementation of the gradient boosting algorithm. XGBoost has proved to be a highly effective ML algorithm. XGBoost has high predictive power and is almost 10 times faster than the other gradient boosting techniques. It also includes a variety of regularization which reduces overfitting and improves overall performance. Hence it is also known as regularized boosting technique

Parameters tuned: subsample- used lower values to prevent overfitting, n_estimators=number of base estimators to be created., learning_rate=controls the contribution of the estimators in the final combination.

def make_submision(test_preds,pred_file):
  test_data['unit_sales'] = test_preds
  submit = test_data.loc[:,('id','unit_sales')]
  pred_file = pd.merge(predictions,submit,on='id')
  pred_file.drop('unit_sales_x',axis = 1,inplace = True)
  pred_file.rename(columns = {"unit_sales_y":"unit_sales"},inplace=True)
  pred_file.to_csv('predictsLGBM.csv',index = False)

  plt.figure(figsize=(15,20))

    if(idx < 9):
      subplot = 550+idx+1
      plt.subplot(subplot)
      temp.groupby('week')['unit_sales'].mean().plot(kind='bar',title = ''+str(item))
    else:
      plt.subplot(5,5,10)
      temp.groupby('week')['unit_sales'].mean().plot(kind='bar',title = ''+str(item))

SUMMARY AND CONCLUSION¶

I started off with merging all the datasets together, then I extracted information from the date column which can be used for sub-setting, extracting visual information or as a feature. We then dropped all duplicates from the data. Then I have done some preprocessing that is required for data before I go ahead and explore/visualize any insights in the data. I noticed the distribution of unit sales for items is normal. Some items are sold everyday while others can be sold in once a year. The model that outperformed the others was the LGM model. It has given me a MAPE score of 63 for validation data. I have tuned some parameters using grid search to find optimal parameters. We see that cluster 14 has the highest sales predicted. This may because of the high number of stores found in the state of Karnataka. We may advise the manager to open more stores of type A. Grocery stores will do well as many people are purchasing grocery products.
